@page "/control-samples/masterpage"
@layout MainLayout
@rendermode InteractiveServer

<PageTitle>MasterPage Recommended Pattern</PageTitle>

<h2>MasterPage - Recommended Pattern</h2>

<div class="alert alert-info" data-audit-control="MasterPage-RecommendedPattern">
    <strong>Recommended usage:</strong> treat <code>MasterPage</code> as the shell host.
    Put the shell markup and <code>ContentPlaceHolder</code> regions in <code>ChildContent</code>,
    then place page-level <code>Content</code> blocks under <code>ChildComponents</code>.
    That keeps the familiar Web Forms tag names while behaving more like a Blazor layout with named sections.
</div>

<h3>How to use it now</h3>

<ol>
    <li>Define the shell once with <code>Head</code> and <code>ChildContent</code>.</li>
    <li>Keep default placeholder content in the shell so pages can migrate incrementally.</li>
    <li>Let each migrated page supply only the <code>Content</code> blocks it actually overrides.</li>
</ol>

<div class="row mt-4">
    <div class="col-lg-6">
        <div class="card h-100">
            <div class="card-header bg-dark text-white">
                <h4 class="mb-0">1. Shell component</h4>
            </div>
            <div class="card-body">
                <p class="text-muted">
                    This is the reusable master-page shell. It owns shared chrome, optional head content,
                    and the placeholder defaults.
                </p>
                <pre><code>&lt;MasterPage&gt;
    &lt;Head&gt;
        &lt;meta name="catalog-shell" content="enabled" /&gt;
    &lt;/Head&gt;
    &lt;ChildContent&gt;
        &lt;header&gt;...shared chrome...&lt;/header&gt;
        &lt;ContentPlaceHolder ID="MainContent" /&gt;
        &lt;ContentPlaceHolder ID="Sidebar" /&gt;
        &lt;ContentPlaceHolder ID="PageActions"&gt;
            Default action from the shell
        &lt;/ContentPlaceHolder&gt;
    &lt;/ChildContent&gt;
&lt;/MasterPage&gt;</code></pre>
            </div>
        </div>
    </div>

    <div class="col-lg-6 mt-4 mt-lg-0">
        <div class="card h-100">
            <div class="card-header bg-success text-white">
                <h4 class="mb-0">2. Child page usage</h4>
            </div>
            <div class="card-body">
                <p class="text-muted">
                    The page does not rebuild the shell. It just contributes named sections under
                    <code>ChildComponents</code>.
                </p>
                <pre><code>&lt;MasterPage&gt;
    &lt;ChildContent&gt;
        ...shell with ContentPlaceHolder regions...
    &lt;/ChildContent&gt;
    &lt;ChildComponents&gt;
        &lt;Content ContentPlaceHolderID="MainContent"&gt;
            Page body
        &lt;/Content&gt;
        &lt;Content ContentPlaceHolderID="Sidebar"&gt;
            Sidebar links
        &lt;/Content&gt;
    &lt;/ChildComponents&gt;
&lt;/MasterPage&gt;</code></pre>
            </div>
        </div>
    </div>
</div>

<h3 class="mt-5">Live Demo: Recommended shell and page contract</h3>

<p>
    This demo shows the new intended pattern directly: the shell owns the layout structure and placeholders,
    while the page contributes only the named content sections it needs.
</p>

<div data-audit-control="MasterPage-GeneratedShell">
    <MasterPage>
        <Head>
            <meta name="sample-masterpage-generated-shell" content="enabled" />
            <style>
                .masterpage-shell-accent {
                    display: inline-block;
                    padding: 0.35rem 0.65rem;
                    border-radius: 999px;
                    background: #e7f1ff;
                    color: #0a58ca;
                    font-size: 0.875rem;
                    font-weight: 600;
                }
            </style>
        </Head>

        <ChildContent>
            <div class="border rounded overflow-hidden bg-white shadow-sm">
                <div class="d-flex justify-content-between align-items-center px-3 py-2 text-white" style="background:#343a40;">
                    <strong data-masterpage-shell-title="true">Contoso.Site.Master</strong>
                    <span class="masterpage-shell-accent">Head-enabled shell</span>
                </div>

                <div class="row g-0">
                    <div class="col-lg-8 p-3">
                        <ContentPlaceHolder ID="MainContent">
                            <p class="mb-0"><em>Default main content from the shell.</em></p>
                        </ContentPlaceHolder>
                    </div>
                    <div class="col-lg-4 border-start bg-light p-3">
                        <h5 class="h6">Sidebar</h5>
                        <ContentPlaceHolder ID="Sidebar">
                            <p class="mb-0">Default sidebar links from Site.Master.</p>
                        </ContentPlaceHolder>
                    </div>
                </div>

                <div class="d-flex justify-content-between align-items-center px-3 py-2 border-top bg-light">
                    <small class="text-muted">Shared footer and action area from the migrated shell.</small>
                    <ContentPlaceHolder ID="PageActions">
                        <button type="button" class="btn btn-outline-secondary btn-sm" disabled data-masterpage-default-action="true">Default action from Site.Master</button>
                    </ContentPlaceHolder>
                </div>
            </div>
        </ChildContent>

        <ChildComponents>
            <Content ContentPlaceHolderID="MainContent">
                <h4 class="mb-2">Catalog overview</h4>
                <p class="mb-2">
                    This content is supplied by the migrated child page and lands in the
                    <code>MainContent</code> slot even though the placeholder renders earlier in the shell.
                </p>
                <ul class="mb-0">
                    <li>Reusable shell contract</li>
                    <li>Named slot wiring through <code>MasterPageContext</code></li>
                    <li>Default slot fallback for untouched regions</li>
                </ul>
            </Content>

            <Content ContentPlaceHolderID="Sidebar">
                <strong>Recently viewed</strong>
                <ul class="mb-0 mt-2">
                    <li>Quarterly Sales</li>
                    <li>Customer Retention</li>
                    <li>Support Queue</li>
                </ul>
            </Content>
        </ChildComponents>
    </MasterPage>
</div>

<div class="alert alert-success mt-3">
    <strong>What to notice:</strong> <code>MainContent</code> and <code>Sidebar</code> are overridden by
    <code>Content</code> blocks, but <code>PageActions</code> is not, so the shell keeps its default button.
    That is the new recommended split: shell structure in <code>ChildContent</code>, page sections in
    <code>ChildComponents</code>, and only the untouched placeholder defaults remain in the shell.
</div>

<pre><code>&lt;MasterPage&gt;
    &lt;Head&gt;
        &lt;meta name="sample-masterpage-generated-shell" content="enabled" /&gt;
    &lt;/Head&gt;
    &lt;ChildContent&gt;
        &lt;ContentPlaceHolder ID="MainContent" /&gt;
        &lt;ContentPlaceHolder ID="Sidebar" /&gt;
        &lt;ContentPlaceHolder ID="PageActions"&gt;
            Default action from Site.Master
        &lt;/ContentPlaceHolder&gt;
    &lt;/ChildContent&gt;
    &lt;ChildComponents&gt;
        &lt;Content ContentPlaceHolderID="MainContent"&gt;
            Child page body
        &lt;/Content&gt;
        &lt;Content ContentPlaceHolderID="Sidebar"&gt;
            Sidebar links
        &lt;/Content&gt;
    &lt;/ChildComponents&gt;
&lt;/MasterPage&gt;</code></pre>

<h3 class="mt-5">Live Demo: Head bridge and default slot fallback</h3>

<p>
    The badge below is styled by CSS emitted from the shell's <code>Head</code> content. This is the same migration
    bridge used for content that originally lived in <code>&lt;head runat="server"&gt;</code>. The page also keeps its
    default action slot because the child page did not supply <code>PageActions</code>.
</p>

<div class="card" data-audit-control="MasterPage-HeadBridge">
    <div class="card-body">
        <p class="mb-2">
            <span class="masterpage-shell-accent">Head-injected styling is active</span>
        </p>
        <p class="mb-0">
            Inspect the document head and you'll find
            <code>&lt;meta name="sample-masterpage-generated-shell" content="enabled"&gt;</code>.
        </p>
    </div>
</div>

<h3 class="mt-5">Live Demo: Visible parameter</h3>

<p>
    Migrated shells still honor the inherited <code>Visible</code> parameter. Toggling it off suppresses the entire shell
    and every placeholder inside it.
</p>

<div data-audit-control="MasterPage-VisibleToggle">
    <button class="btn btn-outline-primary btn-sm" @onclick="ToggleBridgeVisibility">
        @(showBridgeShell ? "Hide bridge shell" : "Show bridge shell")
    </button>

    @if (!showBridgeShell)
    {
        <p class="text-muted mt-3 mb-0" data-masterpage-hidden-message="true">
            The shell is hidden because <code>Visible</code> is <code>false</code>.
        </p>
    }

    <MasterPage Visible="@showBridgeShell">
        <ChildContent>
            <div class="alert alert-secondary mt-3 mb-0" data-masterpage-visibility-shell="true">
                <ContentPlaceHolder ID="VisibilityStatus">
                    <span>Default visibility message.</span>
                </ContentPlaceHolder>
            </div>
        </ChildContent>

        <ChildComponents>
            <Content ContentPlaceHolderID="VisibilityStatus">
                <span>The shell is currently visible and rendering its slot content.</span>
            </Content>
        </ChildComponents>
    </MasterPage>
</div>

<pre><code>&lt;MasterPage Visible="@@showBridgeShell"&gt;
    &lt;ChildContent&gt;
        &lt;ContentPlaceHolder ID="VisibilityStatus"&gt;
            Default visibility message.
        &lt;/ContentPlaceHolder&gt;
    &lt;/ChildContent&gt;
    &lt;ChildComponents&gt;
        &lt;Content ContentPlaceHolderID="VisibilityStatus"&gt;
            The shell is currently visible and rendering its slot content.
        &lt;/Content&gt;
    &lt;/ChildComponents&gt;
&lt;/MasterPage&gt;</code></pre>

<div class="alert alert-warning mt-4">
    <strong>Recommendation:</strong> Use native Blazor layouts for new development.
    The BWFC master-page bridge is most valuable when you need a runnable migration waypoint before fully adopting
    <code>@@layout</code>, <code>@@Body</code>, <code>PageTitle</code>, and <code>HeadContent</code>.
</div>

<div class="card mt-4">
    <div class="card-header bg-info text-white">
        <h5>Migration checklist</h5>
    </div>
    <div class="card-body">
        <ol class="mb-0">
            <li>Keep shared chrome in a reusable shell component.</li>
            <li>Move migrated <code>&lt;head runat="server"&gt;</code> content into the shell's <code>Head</code> parameter or native <code>HeadContent</code>.</li>
            <li>Leave placeholder defaults in place so pages can migrate incrementally.</li>
            <li>When <code>Head</code> and <code>ChildContent</code> are explicit, group page-level <code>Content</code> blocks under <code>&lt;ChildComponents&gt;</code>.</li>
            <li>Plan to replace the bridge with native Blazor layouts once migration pressure is gone.</li>
        </ol>
    </div>
</div>

@code {
    private bool showBridgeShell = true;

    private void ToggleBridgeVisibility()
    {
        showBridgeShell = !showBridgeShell;
    }
}
